WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:03.664
Pneumothorax is a condition where air
enters the pleural space,

2
00:00:04.244 --> 00:00:07.144
disrupting the normal negative pressure
that keeps the lungs expanded.

3
00:00:07.684 --> 00:00:10.104
As a result, part or all of the lung
collapses,

4
00:00:10.685 --> 00:00:13.364
leading to impaired ventilation and
potential hypoxemia.

5
00:00:13.824 --> 00:00:17.364
For respiratory therapists, the key is
recognizing how quickly this

6
00:00:17.364 --> 00:00:19.905
can progress and identifying when it
becomes life-threatening.

7
00:00:20.264 --> 00:00:22.104
There are three major types to know.

8
00:00:22.604 --> 00:00:26.184
A spontaneous pneumothorax occurs without
trauma, often in tall,

9
00:00:26.485 --> 00:00:29.125
thin individuals or patients with
underlying lung disease.

10
00:00:29.485 --> 00:00:33.104
A traumatic pneumothorax results from
injury, such as rib fractures

11
00:00:33.104 --> 00:00:34.205
or penetrating wounds.

12
00:00:34.805 --> 00:00:38.345
The most dangerous form is tension
pneumothorax, where air enters

13
00:00:38.345 --> 00:00:42.365
the pleural space but cannot escape,
causing increasing pressure that

14
00:00:42.365 --> 00:00:45.485
shifts mediastinal structures and
compresses the heart and great vessels.

15
00:00:46.284 --> 00:00:49.345
Pathophysiologically, the problem starts
with air in the pleural space.

16
00:00:49.825 --> 00:00:53.305
This eliminates the negative pressure
needed for lung expansion, causing

17
00:00:53.305 --> 00:00:54.305
alveolar collapse.

18
00:00:54.305 --> 00:00:58.584
As the lung collapses, ventilation
decreases while perfusion may still

19
00:00:58.584 --> 00:01:01.025
occur, creating a ventilation-perfusion
mismatch.

20
00:01:01.904 --> 00:01:05.305
In tension pneumothorax, rising pressure
reduces venous return,

21
00:01:05.785 --> 00:01:09.885
leading to hypotension and  Clinically,
patients often present with sudden

22
00:01:09.885 --> 00:01:11.605
dyspnea and unilateral chest pain.

23
00:01:12.324 --> 00:01:14.625
Breath sounds are decreased or absent on
the affected side,

24
00:01:14.724 --> 00:01:17.025
and you may see tachypnea and hypoxemia.

25
00:01:17.705 --> 00:01:20.565
In tension pneumothorax, look for severe
distress,

26
00:01:21.144 --> 00:01:24.245
tracheal deviation away from the affected
side, hypotension,

27
00:01:24.444 --> 00:01:25.264
and signs of shock.

28
00:01:25.764 --> 00:01:28.644
These are critical red flags that require
immediate intervention.

29
00:01:29.705 --> 00:01:32.565
Diagnosis is often confirmed with chest
x-ray, which may

30
00:01:32.565 --> 00:01:35.224
show a visible pleural line and absence of
lung markings.

31
00:01:35.705 --> 00:01:38.165
However, in a suspected tension
pneumothorax,

32
00:01:38.485 --> 00:01:39.824
you do not wait for imaging.

33
00:01:40.165 --> 00:01:41.605
This is a clinical diagnosis.

34
00:01:42.764 --> 00:01:43.785
Management depends on severity.

35
00:01:44.404 --> 00:01:47.785
Small, stable pneumothoraces may only
require oxygen and monitoring.

36
00:01:48.364 --> 00:01:53.644
Larger or symptomatic cases often require
needle aspiration or chest tube placement to remove

37
00:01:53.644 --> 00:01:55.625
air and allow the lung to re-expand.

38
00:01:56.444 --> 00:02:02.224
Tension pneumothorax is a medical
emergency requiring immediate needle decompression followed by chest tube

39
00:02:02.224 --> 00:02:02.705
insertion.

40
00:02:03.004 --> 00:02:05.805
From an RT perspective, your role is
critical.

41
00:02:06.345 --> 00:02:08.544
You assess breath sounds, oxygenation, and

42
00:02:08.544 --> 00:02:10.824
work of breathing, assist with oxygen
therapy,

43
00:02:11.524 --> 00:02:15.125
monitor for deterioration, and support
procedures like needle decompression and

44
00:02:15.125 --> 00:02:15.764
chest tube setup.

45
00:02:16.085 --> 00:02:20.164
You also help recognize when a patient is
transitioning from stable to unstable.

46
00:02:20.785 --> 00:02:22.384
For board prep, remember this.

47
00:02:22.865 --> 00:02:27.244
Sudden dyspnea plus absent breath sounds
on one side should immediately make you think

48
00:02:27.285 --> 00:02:27.925
pneumothorax.

49
00:02:28.404 --> 00:02:31.925
Add hypotension and tracheal deviation,
and you must act fast

50
00:02:31.925 --> 00:02:33.104
for tension pneumothorax.

